00:43:32,002 --> 00:43:38,073
that -- to not recognize ourselves in each
other. (Applause.)

388
00:43:38,091 --> 00:43:43,103
We think because somebody’s skin is slightly
different, or their hair is slightly different,

389
00:43:44,003 --> 00:43:52,027
or their religious faith is differently expressed,
or they speak a different language that it

390
00:43:52,027 --> 00:43:58,034
justifies somehow us treating them with less
dignity. And that becomes the source of so

391
00:43:58,097 --> 00:44:02,226
many of our problems. And we think somehow
that we make ourselves better by putting other

392
00:44:03,099 --> 00:44:09,520
people down. And that becomes the source of
so many of our problems. When we begin to

393
00:44:09,052 --> 00:44:16,351
see other as somehow less than ourselves -- when
we succumb to these artificial divisions of

394
00:44:16,819 --> 00:44:24,868
faith or sect or tribe or ethnicity -- then
even the most awful abuses are justified in

395
00:44:25,309 --> 00:44:32,270
the minds of those who are thinking in those
ways. And in the end, abusers lose their own

396
00:44:32,027 --> 00:44:39,069
humanity, as well. (Applause.)

397
00:44:39,069 --> 00:44:44,095
Nelson Mandela taught us, “to be free is
not merely to cast off one’s chains, but

398
00:44:44,095 --> 00:44:48,169
to live in a way that respects and enhances
the freedom of others.”

399
00:44:49,069 --> 00:44:53,071
Every one of us is equal. Every one of us
has worth. Every one of us matters. And when

400
00:44:53,089 --> 00:44:57,788
we respect the freedom of others -- no matter
the color of their skin, or how they pray

401
00:44:58,589 --> 00:45:09,700
or who they are or who they love -- we are
all more free. (Applause.) Your dignity depends

402
00:45:09,007 --> 00:45:15,102
on my dignity, and my dignity depends on yours.
Imagine if everyone had that spirit in their

403
00:45:16,065 --> 00:45:25,074
hearts. Imagine if governments operated that
way. (Applause.) Just imagine what the world

404
00:45:25,074 --> 00:45:29,118
could look like -- the future that we could
bequeath these young people.

405
00:45:30,018 --> 00:45:36,097
Yes, in our world, old thinking can be a stubborn
thing. That's one of the reasons why we need

406
00:45:36,097 --> 00:45:44,100
term limits -- old people think old ways.
And you can see my grey hair, I'm getting

407
00:45:45,027 --> 00:45:51,616
old. (Laughter.) The old ways can be stubborn.
But I believe the human heart is stronger.

408
00:45:51,859 --> 00:45:56,935
I believe hearts can change. I believe minds
can open. That’s how change happens. That’s

409
00:45:57,619 --> 00:46:05,490
how societies move forward. It's not always
a straight line -- step by halting step -- sometimes

410
00:46:05,049 --> 00:46:10,148
you go forward, you move back a little bit.
But I believe we are marching, we are pointing

411
00:46:11,048 --> 00:46:14,147
towards ideals of justice and equality.

412
00:46:14,579 --> 00:46:20,658
That’s how your nations won independence
-- not just with rifles, but with principles

413
00:46:21,369 --> 00:46:26,260
and ideals. (Applause.) That's how African
Americans won our civil rights. That's how

414
00:46:26,026 --> 00:46:32,045
South Africans -- black and white -- tore
down apartheid. That's why I can stand before

415
00:46:32,045 --> 00:46:39,064
you today as the first African American President
of the United States. (Applause.)

416
00:46:39,064 --> 00:46:47,115
New thinking. Unleashing growth that creates
opportunity. Promoting development that lifts

417
00:46:48,015 --> 00:46:54,078
all people out of poverty. Supporting democracy
that gives citizens their say. Advancing the

418
00:46:54,078 --> 00:47:01,667
security and justice that delivers peace.
Respecting the human rights of all people.

419
00:47:02,369 --> 00:47:07,200
These are the keys to progress -- not just
in Africa, but around the world. And this

420
00:47:07,002 --> 00:47:08,059
is the work that we can do together.

421
00:47:08,077 --> 00:47:15,084
And I am hopeful. As I prepare to return home,
my thoughts are with that same young man from

422
00:47:16,047 --> 00:47:20,676
Senegal, who said: Here, I have met Africa,
the [Africa] I’ve always believed in. She’s

423
00:47:21,099 --> 00:47:27,196
beautiful and young, full of talent and motivation
and ambition. To which I would simply add,

424
00:47:28,069 --> 00:47:32,142
as you build the Africa you believe in, you
will have no better partner, no better friend

425
00:47:32,799 --> 00:47:35,490
than the United States of America. (Applause.)

426
00:47:35,049 --> 00:48:00,073
God bless Africa. God bless the United States
of America. Thank you very much, everybody.

427
00:48:00,073 --> 00:48:21,141
Thank you. (Applause.)

